description.text:
Laser XY Scanner

Low Cost DIY 3D Printed stepper motor Laser XY Scanner - Draw, Cut, Engrave, or Scan

Laser XY Scanner is an open source stepper motor based scanner.
The components used are low cost and very accessible. This type
of laser scanner is not extremely fast but it can still be used in a
variety of applications. Draw, cut and or point with laser X and Y control.

The circuit:

  • Arduino Nano
    • Monitors small lever switches for X and Y home detection (minimum travel)
    • Controls ULN2003APG high−current darlington drivers
      • Drives 28BYJ-48 5V Stepper Motors
  • 12V TTL 1W/1.6W/2W/445nm/450nm Laser Diode LD Driver
    • Drives 2W 445nm M140 Blue Laser Diode w/ AixiZ aluminum mount and heat sink for 12mm modules

The Arduino code can be found in the project repository.
GitHub Project: https://github.com/ThingEngineer/Laser-XY-Scanner

The Instructable:
https://www.instructables.com/id/Low-Cost-DIY-Stepper-Motor-Laser-XY-Scanner-Cutter/

Video of the Laser XY Scanner in action:
https://youtu.be/hbFObc3SvLU

description.text: There were other trim clips out there but none of them what I needed. This goes on my Toyota Rav4, under the hood. It holds the plastic trim to the metal frame. When I changed out my battery, 2 of them broke, (the black ones are the original, the blue are the tests). I certainly didn't want to go and pay dealership or parts store prices when I have a perfectly good 3D printer. I printed this on my CTC Dual Bizer, running Sailfish 7(something). I printed it in ABS. I also printed them sideways, not strait up and down. If you print them strait up, they will just break, even in ABS. I also printed with 100% infill since they are small parts. Basically, the smaller pin goes into the outer hole. It then separates when passing through the other end and locks in place in the notch, (the notch is small, but it's there, and it seems to hold just fine). You put it on about half way, then when it is inserted all the way, it widens the lower half and keeps it from pulling out. It took several tries to make it work, but when it worked, it worked. Hope this helps someone else that might need one. I designed this using TinkerCad, (Thank you TinkerCad!).

I was trying to be as thorough as possible for the different things people might need out of a model. I've split the star down the middle so you'd need less support material by printing each piece on it's side. I also included a hollowed out version if you'd like to make it lighter and perhaps put some lights on the inside once it's done. And lastly, if your printer can't properly bridge a 3-4 cm gap (which let's face it, many can't) I also included some files with MeshMixer supports added so you don't have to enable support on your printer. They worked really well for me when I was printing the hollowed out version. Just remember, you only need to download the 2 files for the model you choose to print.

description.text:
Update 2018-01-04: I have added single channel, low height versions of this guide. This will reduce feed resistance for printers where the filament guide exit point does not need to be elevated.

This is version 2 of my snap fit filament guide designed primarily for direct drive based extruders (like the Titan Aero) mounted on common aluminum extrusion form factors.

What's New

  • In the original version, rapid forward feeding with a nearly empty spool could cause the spool to hop forward -- off the spool holder. This design feeds from the bottom and a high speed forward travel move will now result in a downward force (onto the spool holder) instead of forward.

  • The back wall of the 2040 version has been thickened to reduce flex over the 40mm length.

  • This design is extremely resistant to back pressure / back feeding of the filament.

  • There are now two filament channels. The first one directs pressure downward when filament is feeding and the second keeps the filament above the carriage, cable chain, etc.

  • The height has been decreased to avoid the filament making contact with the spool as it moves between the two filament channels.

The snap on spool holders shown in the pictures are available here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2537713

Please share your makes!

description.text:
When I bought my DJI Phantom 3 secondhand, it came with a broken gimbal. This is a common problem with the Phantom 3, as the gimbal is not designed very well, with a lot of the construction being made from very thin plastic. I managed to hold everything together with a few pieces of stickytape, but this needs to be done before every flight as it gradually comes off. So I decided to make a more permanent solution.

The in-flight gimbal support is fitted over the top of the gimbal bracket and clips into place. Unlike many other gimbal supports on Thingiverse which are used to prevent damage to the gimbal during transport, this bracket is kept on while flying to hold everything together.

Even if your gimbal is not broken, it would provide additional strength in the event of a crash.

NOTE: The part is sized with no gaps, so depending on which printer you use, and the quality setting, you may need to resize the model in your slicer. My final print was sized to 101% before slicing, and it had a nice tight fit.

Checkout the video to see the gimbal support in action.

remixed_from.title: Extruder plate for wallace and makergear hot-end or j-head

description.text:
The Wallace has an X-Carriage that is very low... If you're using a J-Head with a slot-mount, the nozzle might not reach the bed before the carriage touches it... unless you mount the slot-mount plate UNDER the carriage.  
This adapter fills the gap between the extruder and the J-Head Nozzle Holder if you decide to mount the slot-mount plate under the carriage.

These instructions are for:
  • a 3mm filament J-Head
  • with a Slot-mount plate
  • And a Greg's Wade's hinged extruder
    • 1: Print and finish. Remove any support and use a dremel grinding stone cylinder (like the Dremel #932) to clean up the hole where the nozzle holder is going to be inserted. Use a drill bit or a tap (M4) to clean up the filament path.
    2: Insert the J-Head nozzle holder into the large hole.
    3: Mount the J-Head & Gap Adapter to the Slot-Mount plate.
    4: Bolt the plate to the BOTTOM of the Wallace X-carriage. Use M4x25mm screws.
    5: Place M4 nuts into the base of the extruder, and mount the extruder on TOP of the X-carriage and Gap Adapter. Tighten the M4 screws into the M4 nuts.

Creating a 3-d model of a ternary phase diagram

OpenJSCad code

var res = 64;
var side=100;

var p1 = [0,0];
var p2 = [side,0];
var p3 = [side/2,Math.sqrt(sideside3/4)];

var c1 = [0,0,0];
var c2 = [side,0,0];
var c3 = [p3[0],p3[1],0];

var stackOfTiles = new Array();

function main() {
for ( z=5; z<100; z+=7) {
stackOfTiles.push( CSG.cube({
corner1: [0, 0, z],
corner2: [100, 100, z+0.75]
}));
}

var s1o = CSG.sphere({
center: c1,
radius: 70.5,
resolution: res
});

var s2o = CSG.sphere({
center: c2,
radius: 60.5,
resolution: res
});

var s3o = CSG.sphere({
center: c3,
radius: 50.5,
resolution: res
});

var s1i = CSG.sphere({
center: c1,
radius: 70,
resolution: res
});

var s2i = CSG.sphere({
center: c2,
radius: 60,
resolution: res
});

var s3i = CSG.sphere({
center: c3,
radius: 50,
resolution: res
});

var triangle = polygon([c1,c2,c3]);
var prism = linear_extrude({height:100},triangle);

var outsideSpheres = s1o.union(s2o).union(s3o);
var insideSpheres = s1i.union(s2i).union(s3i);
var slices = outsideSpheres.intersect(union(stackOfTiles));

return union(slices,insideSpheres).intersect(prism);
}

description.text:
This is a hairy type Christmas Tree and accompanying ornaments, designed to be printable at near the maximum size of the Rostock Max V2. The tree itself is 11.25" (286mm) tall, by 9.85" Ø (250mm).

The tree is designed for PLA with a 0.4mm nozzle printed at 0.3mm layer height. If other settings are used the quality may suffer due to the loops of the branches not generating properly.

The ornaments are designed to be printed on any printer capable of single or dual-color extrusion, and in the case of the snowman, tri-color. Ornaments such as the Christmas lights and bell could also achieve the multi-color effect via a layer pause and filament swap.

The ornaments all include a built in hook which will attach to the loops of any hairy type Christmas tree, the Christmas lights are designed for the first and last light to loop inside the tree "branch" to hold in place.

Any file with the suffix "A" "B" or "C" is designed for multi-color, any without a suffix is intended for single color extrusion.

Files designed for ONLY single color:

  • Realistic_Tree
  • 5_Point_Star
  • Tree_Topper

Files designed for 1-2 colors:

  • 10_Point_Star
  • Bell
  • Candy_Cane
  • Chistmas_Lights
  • Elongated_Sphere
  • Sphere_Sliced
  • SphereZig (single color file just called "Sphere")

Files designed for 1-3 Colors (highly recommended as 3)

  • Snowman

For my print all ornaments were printed on a Prusa MK2 Multi-Material Kit. The tree was printed on a Rostock Max V2. The small "presents" are the wipe blocks used on the multicolor prints on the Prusa MK2MM.

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M_jkJWANu84&feature=youtu.be

This is my attempt at creating an affordable lightweight and simple to use binaural microphone for recording "3D" sound. You can learn more about binaural sound here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yd5i7TlpzCk

The project requires a dual microphone lavalier to be placed in the ears you'll be printing. I used the Polsen OLM-20. Because of the long cord, I created a cavity to house much of the excess folded cable.

The total cost of buying the microphone and printing the parts should cost less than $100, versus commercial solutions that cost hundreds.

Notes:

The "Pin" object should be printed with a higher infill than the rest of the components since it's doing so much of the heavy lifting. As of this version, it still remains quite delicate and I have plans to adjust this in the future.

Place an omni lavalier into each ear and then fold the excess wires connecting them into the EarCanals object. Any extra wire that won't fit can be secured with elastic bands. Once everything fits and the lavaliers are visible through the holes in each ear, use glue or acetone to secure Ear A and Ear B to either side of the EarCanals.

Thread the Nut onto the Screw object, and then twist Pin onto the top of Screw. Pin simply slides into the hole at the bottom of EarCanals. You may want to glue the Pin to the EarCanals, but keeping them separate makes it easier to fit everything into a bag.

Now the entire contraption can attach to your camera's hot shoe. Plug in the mic, and start recording binaural audio.

I started with a hotshoe coupler I found on Thingiverse to mount the final product to my camera. I then got a set of ears from cgtrader (https://www.cgtrader.com/free-3d-models/various/various-models/humans-ear-3d-model) and used Wings3D to model everything in between.

Start to finish, the project took me about 2 weeks. This was my first 3D printer project so there was a lot of learning along the way.

title: ABHA Rodin Coil Frame (Phi proportions, 36x36 pattern)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a 400mm or 16" outside diameter ABHA Rodin coil frame and have 3rd order Phi proportions using Tom Barnett research to find the proportions. Here is his video https://youtu.be/kxuU8jYkA1k.
I provided the files for a 250mm, 10" coil frame too, in case you do not want to build a large one.
This is not designed for the Daniel Nunez type coil which has the cross winding and he calls it the POE Coil.
On the Tom Barnett video the smallest inner toroid I call the 1st order coil and the one bigger is the 3rd order since it has the Do=outside coil diameter and the Di=inside coil diameter in the proportions Do:Di=Phi^3 and as such it has the pattern of 36x36 according to Tom Barnett's suggestion. Just as a reminder, Phi is the a constant called the Golden Ratio which is Phi=1.618. See how calculations are done for the different order coils in the image above or in the PDF provided.
The various patterns come from and can be found here https://youtu.be/7pvuTZ5u6Kg which is the YouTube channel of Randy Powell, the discoverer of this modeling.
You can scale this design, of course, but I would not go smaller than Do=200mm or 8", otherwise the ribs/formers get too thin and flimsy.
See images how the winding is going around the coil. The images show one loop only so you can see the path clearly. The colour markings help to see that every 2nd grove has the wire bundle routed through it, on the adjacent former.
This design has 16 ribs or former to try to get as close to the correct wire path as possible. This also makes it simpler as the former are symmetrical all around the ring. Make sure that the tabs on the former are all facing the same way as the slot is not in the center, due to the cable routing, see video here => https://youtu.be/ohHqAKv_6No
I provided the files for a smaller Do=250mm too which is reflected in the file names. Just in case you do not want to build the larger one.

Printer:

Wombot Exilis

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I print straight to the print bed without any foundation or support. For this you need to make sure that your printer sensor is calibrated correctly. I use the CraftWare Version 1.14 as that slicer has a 5 point print calibration procedure set straight 'out of the box', see video below. One of the other things I love about this slicer that it shows visually all the adjustments you make, what it effects and how it will look like. Make sure that the head distance is not too close either. Also this slicer has an ideal speed setup for printing the first layer. As you can see from the video these are very important to lay down the first layer of the filament correctly, especially without using support or foundation.
On the built frame photo, the 2 after the formulas, the green is a scaled down version of the 400mm original design, that is posted here, to 250mm, 10". A ratio of 1 : 400mm = 0.625 : 250mm. This reduced size also allowed me to print 2 formers at the same time. The full size would require it to be printed one by one and would need a 200mm x 200mm, 8"x8", print bed. The one I am printing on is 200mm x 200mm. The black frame is a bit earlier design and it is a 200mm or 8" one scaled down to 0.5.
I also use a PRINTinZ print plate which I purchased from here https://www.printinz.com/printinz-3d-printer-plates/ over a year ago.
I am not affiliated with them in any way, I am only a user and I have no headaches with adhesion since I use this printing plate.
This video shows the 5 step print calibration with the CraftWare slicer generated G-code which is executed before the print starts and the temperatures up to the set levels https://youtu.be/X0mD2oPemrQ. You can also see the PRINTinZ print plate, in this case the white side up. The other side is black and can also be printed on.
This video shows what kind of printing speed have better success with the first layer without any support https://youtu.be/lDmnbPZJNDw. This is what CraftWare sets by default, of course you can manipulate all this.

Information for future design related to this one

I have opted for this 400mm outside diameter size as I want to use it as a basis for future design where we can nest these coils as suggested by Tom Barnett. I believe we should investigate the nested Rodin ABHA coils and the various effects this may produce, see configuration image below. The green one represent this design, which is the 3rd order Rodin coil. The inner pink one is the very first one in the nesting which is a 1st order Rodin coil. The 400mm outside diameter will allow a good size inner 1st order coil to be constructed.

Since this project I actually designed the above mentioned nested ABHA Rodin coil which you can find here => https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2749144

title: Shapeoko 2 Altocraft Rotary Tool Spindle Mount

description.text: This is an augmented spindle mount for the (stock) rotary tool that comes with the Shapeoko 2.  Assembled as designed, the Z axis travel was severely limited due to the top of the rotary tool running into the Z axis thrust bearing plate/motor mount.  These inserts fit inside the stock metal mounts and bolt together using the stock 5mm bolts.  No additional hardware is necessary.  Best of all, this maximizes Z travel:  With these mounts I've got 3.25 inches of Z travel (assuming you use a 1/2 inch or longer end mill).  This is with the Z-axis makerslide flush with the bottom of the Z carriage.  I had significantly less travel with the stock configuration or the other printed spindle holders.

I used a fairly "solid" infill and printed in ABS.  It took about 1.5 hours to print all four pieces.  
Print out the four pieces:  
"Lower Fixed" fits into the metal block on the bottom of the Z axis carrage and "Lower Clamp" holds the Altocraft spindle in place using the stock bolts. The lower clamps are positioned just below the tapered section.  
"Upper Fixed" fits into the metal block on the top of the Z axis carrage and "Upper Clamp" holds the Altocraft spindle in place using the stock bolts.  The upper clamps are position above the motor brush access screws and below the switch, making sure to leave the cooling vents uncovered.  I've found that placing the brush access screws in contact with the underside of the upper clamp works well.  
Don't over-tighten.  As designed there is a 2mm gap between the pieces.  This gap goes to 1mm when tight.  I cracked mine by over-tightening it, but it is still working.  
Note: I've altered the "Upper clamp" because I see some stress lines developing on the version 0_4.  Nothing big, but it will help a little. 0_5 is the new version.

comments.text: Awsome design. It got me about 2.5in more Z height at the expense of about 3/4in of Y. If I do not use the back pieces, I might get 1/2in back and it would probably work just as good. Oops...no it wouldn't. I would not get that added Z height without the 2nd piece.

Notes:

This print took me over 30 hours.
Steps to make it work;
1) print the adapter (obvious I know)
2) dismantle your old Ni-Cad battery pack, you will need to keep the top plat, terminals attached to the top cell (with wire) and the 2 side clips.
3) snip off the two tabs at the back of the top plate.
4) Solder an extra wire to the terminal that was attached to the top cell (this connects to the posertive terminal).
5) You need two prongs that the new batterp pack slides into. I used one of the long tags off the old berrety, pack and cut it in half.
6) Solder the 2 loose wires from the terminal to the prongs.
7) You will need to secure the terminal block to the end of the top plate (I just filled the caverty with hot glue). All that matters is that the terminal plate doesn't move.
8) Mount the 2 prongs into the adapter plate as shown (I used the soldering iron to heat the terminals so that they stayed fixed).
9) Squize the top plate onto the adapter plate ( but not all the way) To help with this process I put a small shamfer around each hole on the plate.
9) before you completely squize the two parts together, put the 2 clips into their position on the top plate.
10) Completely squize the two plates togeter.
11) Connect the adapter to the drill.
12) find two small depth screws and drill a pilot hole in the adapter through the clips so that the adapter plate wont seperate from the drill.
13) connect the X Finity Plus batterp pack and it's all done.

Design intent is to utilize plasma cutting to make the the plates / rings / valve petals, and also for the sheet metal blanks to roll and weld to form the intake and combustion chamber. Plan is to run this off a large carburetor with gasoline, so throttle control is possible and the carburetor will handle making sure the air/fuel ratio is right. It will have to be started with a shop-vac on the tail end of the engine, since carburetors usually don't respond well to positive pressure going through them like the typical leaf-blower method of starting injector-based pulsejets.

DXF files lay out the assembly (no dimensions yet, but units are in English) and after sheets of layout views, then each part profile for cutting has been placed in a dxf of its own for ease of loading into the torch machine software.

There are .step and .iges solid part files included here, for anyone who wants to look at the solid 3D model in CAD software. description.text:
I made these parts to mount a print bed on a frame of 2020 aluminium extrusions in my Voron 3d printer. It consists of three parts:

  • Linear bearing holder. These are designed to be a press fit for LM8LUU bearings. If it will not fit properly, adjust the hole dimensions to fit. If it is too loose, it can also be affixed with a piece of steel wire. The bracket ends are designed to line up with the grooves in the bearing to lock them in. Can be mounted either direction. Make four of these.
  • Z leadscrew nut bracket. Designed to fit the nuts I happened to have (which seem to be pretty common), but can be customized to fit others. Can also go either way, I chose to mount mine "upside down" from how they are printed, and the nut below, but that is mostly due to my leadscrews being a bit too short. Print two of these.
  • Bed support brackets. Mounts to the 2020 rail on one side, and has a hole for bed support screws/posts on another. If you have thumbscrews to adjust you may want to change the size of these a bit. Make four of these (if you have 4-point support), you may want to mirror two of them.

Note that the bearing and z-nut brackets need to match. On a Voron, the center of the steel rods and the leadscrews are in the same plane, and these brackets (with dimensions provided here) have the face of the 2020 extrusions 15mm from that central plane. If you change the z-nut bracket for a different size, adjust bearing holders to match.

description.text:
This is a wire brace for the Monoprice Select Mini heated bed. This is used when you re-route the bed wires out the back and is intended to provide support to the wires at the bed. This was designed so that you could install it after you've routed the wires, there's an opening in the support loop so you don't have to feed the wires through. The wires are then secured in place using a zip tie so it's easy to remove it for maintenance. The wire brace is held in place by the screws that hold the rods of the y-axis. I recommend installing this one screw at a time so the y-axis assembly stays relatively intact. I also used some wire bundle wrap, as seen in the photos, similar to the bundle that goes to the hotend. I found this at the hardware store and is the 3mm variety. This isn't necessary though, a few gently tightened zip ties along the bundle will do just fine.
